{"Body": "<p>Figures obtained by the University Times show that less than 40% of the &euro;14.6m collected from the student service charge is being used for its stated purpose. The majority of the revenue is instead used to cover the cuts in the main funding the College receives from Government.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">The student service charge, sometimes called the registration fee currently stands at &euro;1,500 and is paid by all EU students. The Students&rsquo; Unions have long complained that the charge was being used to fund core academic facilities such as the library instead of student services such as the health centre or careers advisory service. While relevant legislation is vague on what the charge covers, the admission is at odds with figures presented to the Oireachtas Education Committee by the College in January this year, which claimed that expenditure on student services of &euro;31.1m in 2008/9 far outstripped income from the charge. The figures obtained by the Times show the comparable amount as &euro;4.8m, and no longer includes academic services such as library costs.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">The figures were compiled as part of a new agreement by the College on the presentation of the controversial charge. This arises from a report by the Working Party on the Student Registration Charge, chaired by the Dean of Students. The report&rsquo;s recommendations adopted by the College Board, established a Student Services Charge Consultative Group, with 50 per cent student representation, which will consider the composition and disbursement of the charge revenues in future.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">Speaking to the University Times, Student&rsquo;s Union President Nikolai Trigoub-Rotnem welcomed the establishment of the consultative group, saying &ldquo;at least now Trinity is being honest that the student service charge is being used as fees by the back door&rdquo;. The Union&rsquo;s Education Officer, Jen Fox said that while &ldquo;the acknowledgement from the Provost that the student registration charge is being used to soak up the reduction in the core grant&rdquo; was to be welcomed, it was still a &ldquo;blatant misuse\n<script src=\"js/tiny_mce/themes/advanced/langs/en.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\nof students&rsquo; registration fees&rdquo;.</span></p>", "Imageurl": "<p>Figures obtained by the University Times show that less than 40% of the &euro;14.6m collected from the student service charge is being used for its stated purpose. The majority of the revenue is instead used to cover the cuts in the main funding the College receives from Government.</p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">The student service charge, sometimes called the registration fee currently stands at &euro;1,500 and is paid by all EU students. The Students&rsquo; Unions have long complained that the charge was being used to fund core academic facilities such as the library instead of student services such as the health centre or careers advisory service. While relevant legislation is vague on what the charge covers, the admission is at odds with figures presented to the Oireachtas Education Committee by the College in January this year, which claimed that expenditure on student services of &euro;31.1m in 2008/9 far outstripped income from the charge. The figures obtained by the Times show the comparable amount as &euro;4.8m, and no longer includes academic services such as library costs.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">The figures were compiled as part of a new agreement by the College on the presentation of the controversial charge. This arises from a report by the Working Party on the Student Registration Charge, chaired by the Dean of Students. The report&rsquo;s recommendations adopted by the College Board, established a Student Services Charge Consultative Group, with 50 per cent student representation, which will consider the composition and disbursement of the charge revenues in future.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p4\"><span class=\"s2\">Speaking to the University Times, Student&rsquo;s Union President Nikolai Trigoub-Rotnem welcomed the establishment of the consultative group, saying &ldquo;at least now Trinity is being honest that the student service charge is being used as fees by the back door&rdquo;. The Union&rsquo;s Education Officer, Jen Fox said that while &ldquo;the acknowledgement from the Provost that the student registration charge is being used to soak up the reduction in the core grant&rdquo; was to be welcomed, it was still a &ldquo;blatant misuse\n<script src=\"js/tiny_mce/themes/advanced/langs/en.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\nof students&rsquo; registration fees&rdquo;.</span></p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "765", "Heading": "Under 40% of registration fee spent on services"}